04028nam a22006975i 9781501744570DE-B159720191126113341.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191126s2019    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017445707 a10.7591/97815017445702doi  a(DE-B1597)534150  a(OCoLC)1125107470  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPR878.P68L36 1998 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a823/.8093551 aLangbauer, Laurie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNovels of Everyday Life :bThe Series in English Fiction, 1850-1930 /cLaurie Langbauer. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tI. Minor Fiction, Endless Progress: Toward a Feminist Ethics -- t2. The Everyday as Everything: Pushing the Limits of Culture in Trollope's Series Fiction -- t3. The City, the Everyday, and Boredom: The Case of Sherlock Holmes -- t4. Unbegun and Unfinished: Race, Modernism, and the Series as a Tradition -- tAfterword: '"'"Enough!" -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLaurie Langbauer argues that our worldview is shaped not just by great public events but also by the most overlooked and familiar aspects of common life-"the everyday." This sphere of the everyday has always been a crucial component of the novel, but has been ignored by many writers and critics and long associated with the writing of women. Focusing on the linked series of novels characteristic of later Victorian and early modern fiction-such as Margaret Oliphant's Carlingford Chronicles or the Sherlock Holmes stories-she investigates how authors make use of the everyday as a foundation to support their versions of realism.What happens when-in the series novel, or in contemporary theory-the everyday becomes a site of contestation and debate? Langbauer pursues this question through the novels of Margaret Oliphant, Charlotte Yonge, Anthony Trollope, and Arthur Conan Doyle-and in the writings of Dorothy Richardson, Virginia Woolf, and John Galsworthy as they reflect on their Victorian predecessors. She also explores accounts of the everyday in the works of such theorists as Henri Lefebvre, Michel de Certeau, and Sigmund Freud, as well as materialist critics, including George Lukacs, Max Horkheimer, and Theodor Adorno. Her work shows how these writers link the series and the everyday in ways that reveal different approaches to comprehending the obscurity that makes up daily life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Nov 2019) 4aEngland. 4aFiction & Short Stories. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501744570423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501744570.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG